                  <hi rend="smallCaps">
                     <persName id="t18401123-name-117" type="witnessName">
                        <interp inst="t18401123-name-117" type="gender" value="male"></interp>
                        <interp inst="t18401123-name-117" type="surname" value="CORTON"></interp>
                        <interp inst="t18401123-name-117" type="given" value="FRANCIS LEAR"></interp>FRANCIS LEAR CORTON</persName>
                  </hi>. I am errand-boy to Mr. Bailey. On the 14th of November I was in Bishops-gate-street, and saw the prisoner at</p>
               <xptr type="pageFacsimile" doc="184011230008"></xptr>
               <p>the prosecutor's door, looking at a hat—I watched him for about two minutes—he looked all over it, took it off the stand, and went up the court with it—I directly went in and told Mr. Pound, who went up the court and caught him.</p>
               <p>
                  <hi rend="smallCaps">
                     <persName id="t18401123-name-118" type="witnessName">
                        <interp inst="t18401123-name-118" type="gender" value="male"></interp>
                        <interp inst="t18401123-name-118" type="surname" value="POUND"></interp>
                        <interp inst="t18401123-name-118" type="given" value="JOHN"></interp>JOHN POUND</persName>
                  </hi>. This is my hat—I observed the prisoner lurking about my window and watched him—something occurred in the shop to draw my attention off, and I forgot it for a moment, till Corton came in and gave me information—I went up the court and met the prisoner a few yards up coming towards me, without the hat—Corton said, "That is the man"—he said he was not, but the man had gone into a public-house with the hat—I collared, took him to the public-house, and asked the landlord if a man had come in with a hat—he said, "No"—he went out into the court with a candle, and returned with the hat.</p>
               <p>
